one of the following correctly describes a key step in lymphocyte development?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["T cells undergo negative selection in the thymic cortex","Positive selection eliminates strongly self-reactive T cells","B cells undergo negative selection in the thymus","Negative selection eliminates cells that fail to recognise self antigens","T cells undergo positive selection in the thymic cortex"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe development of T and B lymphocytes occurs in different primary lymphoid organs and involves distinct selection processes:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ET cell development (in thymus):\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ET cells undergo positive selection in the thymic cortex\u003C/strong\u003E. During positive selection in the cortex, T cells that can appropriately recognise self-major histocompatibility complex (MHC) molecules are selected to survive. This ensures functional T cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter positive selection, T cells move to the medulla where\u003Cstrong\u003E negative selection \u003C/strong\u003Eoccurs - eliminating\u003Cstrong\u003E strongly self-reactive T cells\u003C/strong\u003E to prevent autoimmunity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EB cell \u003C/strong\u003Edevelopment (in bone marrow):\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EB cells develop entirely within the bone marrow through stages including pro-B, pre-B, and immature B cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThey undergo their own selection processes within the bone marrow to eliminate self-reactive cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["T cells develop in the thymus through positive selection (survival of cells recognising self-MHC) and negative selection (elimination of s